splash: keep Dart full-bleed but stop stretching the native splash

The user uploaded the splash artwork (a 1:1 square Talaa logo on an
orange dunes background) and asked again for it to fill the entire
screen on its own.  Two fixes layered on top of each other:

Native (cold-start)
* ``background_image: assets/...png`` was reverted back to
  ``image: assets/...png``.  background_image generates a
  ``<bitmap android:gravity=fill />`` drawable, which scales the
  bitmap with fitXY semantics — i.e. stretches it along both axes
  to fill the screen.  On a 9:19 device that visibly squashed the
  square artwork for the half-second between surface creation and
  the first Flutter frame.  Centred-icon mode preserves the
  artwork's aspect ratio on a brand-orange backdrop and looks crisp.
* Re-ran flutter_native_splash:create so all Android drawables and
  iOS launch storyboards regenerated accordingly.

Dart (in-app)
* SplashPage keeps SizedBox.expand + BoxFit.cover, so once Flutter
  takes over (<1s after launch) the artwork covers every pixel of
  the screen.  Edges may be cropped — that's the unavoidable
  trade-off when a 1:1 source has to fill a 9:19 surface without
  distortion — but the centred Talaa logo always stays inside the
  visible region.

flutter analyze: 0 issues across the workspace.
